Project Description - AllLife Credit Card Customer Segmentation¶

Background¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalised campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the back poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customers queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Objective¶

To identify different segments in the existing customer based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank.

To find¶

  • How many different segments of customers are there?
  • How are these segments different from each other?
  • What are the recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers?

Data Description¶

Data is of various customers of a bank with their credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customer has contacted the bank for any queries, different channels include visiting the bank, online and through a call centre.

Data Dictionary¶

  • Sl_No: Serial Number
  • Customer Key: Customer Identification Key
  • Avg_Credit_Limit: Average Credit Limit for the customer
  • Total_Credit_Cards: Number of Credit Cards customer has
  • Total_visits_bank: Number of times customer visited the bank
  • Total_visits_online: Number of times customer visited the bank website (online)
  • Total_calls_made: Number of times customer called bank

Finding percentage of outliers, in each column of the data, using IQR¶

In [26]:
Q1 = dataCC.quantile(0.25) #25th percentile           
Q3 = dataCC.quantile(0.75) #75th percentile

#Inter Quantile Range (75th perentile - 25th percentile) 
IQR = Q3 - Q1                          

#Finding lower and upper bounds based on IQR. All values outside these bounds are considered outliers
lower=Q1-1.5*IQR                        
upper=Q3+1.5*IQR

Key observations based on EDA¶

  • % or number of customers with higher average credit limit is very less (around 10% only)
  • % or number of customers visiting the bank often are very less (80% make less than 4 visits)
  • % or number of customers visiting the bank website often are very less (90% make less than 5 visits)
  • % or number of customers using calls to communicate with the bank are less (80% make less than 6 calls)
  • From the above observations, it is clear that, customers are not using the bank support services much, bank can focus more on improvng the service delivery model, making sure that the customer requests or queries are resolved faster, that way more customers will make use of the support services
  • Avg_Credit_Limit has +ve correlation with Total_Credit_Cards which makes sense. It has +ve correlation with Total_visits_online, this means that customers accessing online banking uses more credit cards.
  • Total_Credit_Cards has some +ve correlation with Total_visits_bank, which means that customers visiting the bank often tend to use more credit card services
  • Total_visits_bank has -ve correlation with Total_calls_made and Total_visits_online, which make sense, customers using phone calls to interact with the bank and online banking tend to make less visits to the bank directly

Scaling data before clustering¶

  • It is important to scale the data and make different features on the same scale before doing unsupervised learning techniques, since unsupervised learning algorithms find similarity between data points and group them in clusters based on distance measures and the distance measures are scale dependent.
In [44]:
# Scaling the dataset before clustering
#Here we are doing scaling using StandardScaler, it can also be done using z-score
scaler = StandardScaler()
dataCC_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(dataCC)

Should we do PCA??¶

  • PCA can be used to reduce dimensions, if the dataset has too many variables and there is a possibility of 'curse of dimensionality'
  • PCA can also be used to remove multicollinearity to make the variables independent
  • In the given dataset, from pairplot and heatmap, we have seen that, there are no strong correlation between variables
  • And there are only 5 variables in this given dataset
  • Considering these points, I believe, we do not need to do PCA for dimensionality reduction, will try using PCA transformed dataset on K-means and Hierarchical clustering to see if that gives a diff result
  • We can apply PCA on the dataset to find patterns in data, which helps to identify clusters

Checking Silhouette Score¶

  • Silhouette score for a set of data points is used to measure how dense and well-separated the clusters are
  • Silhouette score takes into consideration the intra-cluster distance between the sample and other data points within the same cluster and inter-cluster distance between the sample and the next nearest cluster
  • The silhouette score falls within the range -1 to +1
  • The silhouette score of 1 means that the clusters are very dense and nicely separated. The score of 0 means that clusters are overlapping. The score of less than 0 means that data belonging to clusters may be wrong/incorrect
In [59]:

    score = silhouette_score(dataCC_scaled_df, predict)

Checking Silhouette plots for different values of k to find optimal number of clusters¶

  • Trying values of k below and above the optimal value (3) found from Silhouette Score (2,3,4,5,6)
  • Silhouette plots can be used to select the most optimal value of the K (number of cluster) in K-means clustering
  • The aspects to look out for in Silhouette plots are
    • Cluster scores below the average silhouette score (good if all clusters are above average silhouette score)
    • Wide fluctuations in the size of the clusters (good if the size of clusters is more uniform)
    • The thickness of the silhouette plot (shows the number of data points in a cluster)

Business Recommendations based on K-means¶

  • Cluster 0: This cluster can be thought of as a group of customers who prefer to call bank for diff services, have less number of credit cards, have less interaction with bank online and through direct visits

    • Recommendation:

      • Based on the given dataset,this group is almost 34% of customers.Since these customers prefer to call the bank and have less number of credit cards, bank marketing team can call these customers as part of personalised campaign and talk to them more about credit cards offered by bank, their benefits and even give them some offers to make them use more credit card related products.

      • In another way, we can think that these customers prefer interactions through calls, may be because they are not happy with the online services provided, which bank can consider as an improvement area. This group has less credit card usage, by improving services through call and focusing on enabling better online interactions for this group, bank can improve customer satisfaction, which in turn makes the customers use more produtcs like credit cards.

      • Less credit card usage for this group indicates gap in credit card services provided through calls

  • Cluster 1: This cluster can be thought of as a group of customers who prefer direct bank visits, have more number of credit cards than cluster 0 customers, have less interaction with bank online and through calls

    • Recommendation:
      • Based on the given dataset,this group is almost 58%(more than half) of customers.Since these customers prefer to visit the bank in person and use less online banking, bank marketing team can talk to them when they visit the bank about products (credit cards etc), about benefits of using bank website for their interactions with the bank. Also have a dedicated personalised campaign desk at the bank to focus these customers and know more about their interests on various products including credit cards and find how to make them use more of these bank products.
      • In another way, we can think that these customers prefer interactions through direct visits, may be because they are not happy with the online services provided and not happy with services provided through calls, which bank can consider as an improvement area.By improving services through calls and services provided online, bank can improve customer satisfaction, which in turn makes the customers use more produtcs like credit cards.

  • Cluster 2: This cluster can be thought of as a group of customers who prefer online interactions with bank, have more number of credit cards than cluster 0 and 1 customers, have less interaction with bank through calls and direct visits

    • Recommendation:

      • Based on the given dataset,this group is only 8% of customers, but contribute most towards credit card usage. Since these customers prefer to access bank website for their interactions with the bank, bank marketing team can launch personalised campaign and other services online for these customers, give them option to use chat bots etc to know more about their interests on various products including credit cards, and find out how to retain these customers in terms of credit card usage and improve further more

      • Bank might prefer more customers to start using online services. By improving services provided online, resolving queries faster and better addressing gaps in services, adding more and more services to online website, bank can make more customers move to this cluster, which in turn helps bank reduce manual work load and staff can better focus on other areas

      • Highest credit card usage for this group indicates credit card services provided online are good and can be thought of using for other 2 categories

Hierarchical Clustering¶

  • Going to use cophenetic correlation and dendrograms to find the optimal value of clusters
  • cophenetic correlation is a measure of the correlation between the distance of points in feature space and distance on dendrogram
  • closer it is to 1, the better is the clustering

Linkage methods and distance metrics¶

  • We will work with distance metrics - euclidean,chebyshev,mahalanobis,cityblock and linkage methods - single,complete,average,weighted,centroid,median,ward
  • 'centroid', 'median','ward' linkage methods requires Euclidean distance metric
  • So we will first calculate 'cophenetic correlation' with other distance metrics and different linkage methods
  • Then we will calculate 'cophenetic correlation' with euclidean distance and different linkage methods

#finds out the cophenetic correlation for different distance measures and linkage methods
distance_metrics = [ 'chebyshev','mahalanobis','cityblock']
linkage_methods = ['single', 'complete', 'average','weighted']
high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0,0]
cophenet_corr_dm_lm = []
for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(dataCC_scaled_df_hc, metric=dm, method=lm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z , pdist(dataCC_scaled_df_hc))
        #print('Cophenetic correlation for distance metrics {} and linkage method {} is {}'.format(dm,lm,c))
        cophenet_corr_dm_lm.append([lm,dm,c])               
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm

# List of all linkage methods to check
methods = ['single',
           'average', 
           'complete',
           'centroid',
           'ward',
          'weighted',
          'median']

compare_cols = ['Linkage Method', 'Cophenetic Coefficient']
compare = []

# Create a subplot image
fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(methods), 1, figsize=(15, 30))

# Loop through the list of all linkage methods defined in the list 'methods'

# Get linkage, plot dendrogram, calculate cophenetic coefficient

for i, method in enumerate(methods):
    
    Z = linkage(dataCC_scaled_df_hc, metric='euclidean', method=method)

    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i]);
    
    axs[i].set_title(f'Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)')
    
    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(dataCC_scaled_df_hc))
    
    axs[i].annotate(f'Cophenetic\nCoefficient\n{coph_corr:0.2f}', 
                    (0.80, 0.80),
                    xycoords='axes fraction')
    
    compare.append([method, coph_corr])

Insights from Hierarchical Clustering (Cluster labels change with different linkage methods - insights are based on ward linkage)¶

  • Cluster 0:

    • Avg_Credit_Limit is medium, when compared to other 2 clusters
    • Number of credit cards is also medium, when compared to other 2 clusters
    • Number of visits to bank is highest, when compared to other 2 clusters
    • Number of online website visits is lowest for this cluster
    • Number of calls made to bank is medium, when compared to other 2 clusters
    • Number of data points in this cluster is more than other 2 clusters
    • This cluster can be thought of as a group of customers who prefer direct bank visits, have more number of credit cards than cluster 1 customers, have less interaction with bank online and through calls

  • Cluster 1:

    • Avg_Credit_Limit is lowest for this cluster
    • Number of credit cards is also lowest for this cluster
    • Number of visits to bank is medium, when compared to other 2 clusters
    • Number of online website visits is also medium, when compared to other 2 clusters
    • Number of calls made to bank is highest, when compared to other 2 clusters
    • Number of data points in this cluster is in between when comparing all 3 clusters
    • This cluster can be thought of as a group of customers who prefer to call bank for diff services, have less number of credit cards, have less interaction with bank online and through direct visits

  • Cluster 2:

    • Avg_Credit_Limit is highest, when compared to other 2 clusters
    • Number of credit cards is also highest, when compared to other 2 clusters
    • Number of visits to bank is lowest for this cluster
    • Number of online website visits is highest for this cluster
    • Number of calls made to bank is lowest, when compared to other 2 clusters
    • Number of data points in this cluster is less than other 2 clusters
    • This cluster can be thought of as a group of customers who prefer online intercations with bank, have more number of credit cards than cluster 0 and 1 customers, have less interaction with bank through calls and direct visits

Business Recommendations based on Hierarchical Clustering¶

  • Cluster 0: This cluster can be thought of as a group of customers who prefer direct bank visits, have more number of credit cards than cluster 1 customers, have less interaction with bank online and through calls

    • Recommendation:
      • Based on the given dataset,this group is almost 58%(more than half) of customers.Since these customers prefer to visit the bank, bank marketing team can talk to them when they visit the bank about products (credit cards etc), about benefits of using bank website for their interactions with the bank. Also have a dedicated personalised campaign desk at the bank to focus these customers and know more about their interests on various products including credit cards and find how to make them use more of these bank products
      • In another way, we can think that these customers prefer interactions through direct visits, may be because they are not happy with the online services provided and not happy with services provided through calls, which bank can consider as an improvement area.By improving services through calls and services provided online, bank can improve customer satisfaction, which in turn makes the customers use more produtcs like credit cards.

  • Cluster 1: This cluster can be thought of as a group of customers who prefer to call bank for diff services, have less number of credit cards, have less interaction with bank online and through direct visits

    • Recommendation:
      • Based on the given dataset,this group is almost 34% of customers.Since these customers prefer to call the bank and have less number of credit cards, bank marketing team can call these customers as part of personalised campaign and talk to them more about credit cards offered by bank, their benefits and even give them some offers to make them use more credit card related products
      • In another way, we can think that these customers prefer interactions through calls, may be because they are not happy with the online services provided, which bank can consider as an improvement area. This group has less credit card usage, by improving services through call and focusing on enabling better online interactions for this group, bank can improve customer satisfaction, which in turn makes the customers use more produtcs like credit cards.
      • Less credit card usage for this group indicates gap in credit card services provided through calls

  • Cluster 2: This cluster can be thought of as a group of customers who prefer online interactions with bank, have more number of credit cards than cluster 0 and 1 customers, have less interaction with bank through calls and direct visits

    • Recommendation:
      • Based on the given dataset,this group is only 8% of customers, but contribute most towards credit card usage.Since these customers prefer to access bank website for their interactions with the bank, bank marketing team can launch personalised campaign online for these customers, give them option to use chat bots etc to know more about their interests on various products including credit cards, and find out how to retain these customers in terms of credit card usage and improve further more
      • Bank might prefer more customers to start using online services. By improving services provided online, resolving queries faster and better addressing gaps in services, adding more and more services to online website, bank can make more customers move to this cluster, which in turn helps bank reduce manual work load and staff can better focus on other areas
      • Highest credit card usage for this group indicates credit card services provided online are good and can be thought of using for other 2 categories

Compare K-means clustering and Hierarchical clustering¶

  • Here is the comparison of clusters formed using K-means and Hierarchical clustering methods
  • This comparison is between 3 clusters formed using K-means and 3 clusters formed using Hierarchical clustering

1. Silhouette Score

  • Silhouette Score for K-means with 3 clusters is 0.5174 (with PCA it is 0.6840)
  • Silhouette Score for Hierarchical clustering with 3 clusters is 0.5174 (with PCA it is 0.6839)
  • When Silhouette Score is more close to 1 that shows more compact clusters. Both the scores are very close (almost same), which shows that both methods are equally good in producing better clusters for this given problem statement

2. Number of clusters

  • Elbow curve shows 3 as optimal number of clusters for K-means, when Silhouette Score is calculated for 3 and 4 number of clusters, it is found that 3 is the optimal number of clusters

  • Dendrogram using ward linkage shows 3 or 4 as optimal number of clusters for Hierarchical clustering, based on Silhouette Score, 3 is the optimal number of clusters here

  • Number of clusters formed by both methods are same, which again shows both methods are equally good for the given problem statement

3. Size of clusters

  • K-mean produced 3 clusters with number of data points 386,224,50
  • Hierarchical clustering produced 3 clusters with number of data points 387,223,50
  • Number of data points in clusters are almost same for both methods, shows both methods are giving almost same results

4. Cluster profile

  • Both K-means and Hierarchical clustering produced below 3 clusters of customers, only the cluster labels differ between the two methods
    • A group of customers who prefer direct bank visits, medium credit card usage, have less interaction with bank online and through calls
    • Another group of customers who prefer to call bank more,use less number of credit cards,have less interaction with bank online and through direct visits
    • Third group of customers who prefer online banking, use more credit cards,have less interaction with bank through calls and direct visits

5. Execution Time

  • When it comes to execution time, K-means is faster than Hierarchical clustering, this is because K-means is linear in the number of data objects whereas Hierarchical is quadratic. So Hierarchical is not ideal for larger datasets. But Hierarchical is flexible and we do not need to input the number of clusters to begin.

  • For this given dataset, since it has only 660 data points, we can use either of these methods, and we already saw that both ar equally good.

Conclusion¶

  • Based on the clustering analysis done on given dataset using K-means and Hierarchical clustering, both give us 3 clusters, which are 3 independent groups of customers with different profiles.

  • Since both methods give very similar results, either of them can be used to cluster this dataset (or similar dataset in future). If the data volume is large, K-means is better option.

  • Insights and business recommendations based on both K-means and Hierarchical clustering are already given in the respective sections in this notebook

  • To summarize, these are the 3 clusters of customers

    • A group of customers who prefer direct bank visits, medium credit card usage, have less interaction with bank online and through calls. This group has highest number of customers (58%)
    • Another group of customers who prefer to call bank more,use less number of credit cards,have less interaction with bank online and through direct visits. This group has 34% of customers.
    • Third group of customers who prefer online banking, use more credit cards,have less interaction with bank through calls and direct visits. This group has only 8% of customers.

  • If the bank wants to have more customers using online services, bank can focus on moving more customers from other 2 clusters to this smaller group with more online interactions and credit card usage by improving services provided online, resolving queries faster and better addressing gaps in services, adding more and more services to online website. This in turn helps bank reduce manual work load on staff.
